Prologue
"Please!" pleaded Queen Eirwen. "Don't send her away! She's just a child!" The King of Ice looked down from his throne at his wife, his royal advisor beside him. He had just become a father. This thought made him frown.
The little girl resembled her mother a great deal: pale blue eyes, white hair streaked with blue strands. The King of Ice thought that having a daughter would make him appear weak. After all, he had only sons up until now.
"Your only options are to kill your child or to send her back into nature. That is her punishment for your bad behavior, Eirwen." He spat out her name as if it were poison. He always did.
Frostwell had not always been one kingdom. It had been split in two, the North and the South. In the north, the non-magical realm. In the south, a kingdom filled with fantastic representations of power. Due to the greed of the North, the two realms tore apart in an endless war, until the South offered a truce.
The South was cornered, and its royal family would have done anything to stop the bloodshed. They proposed that their only princess become the queen of the North and bear a son destined to be the future king. Then, the South would have allied with the North to form one kingdom. The North agreed, and Princess Eirwen married Prince Akull.
"Please, Your Highness, in exchange for my child's life, do with me whatever you will, imprison me, banish me, or even kill me," pleaded Queen Eirwen, holding her child tightly in her arms.
The King of Ice lowered his gaze upon his wife, disgust in his eyes. Perhaps, perhaps he might pity her. The one he had lived with for twenty-two years, who had always cared for him in his darkest hours, who had given birth to his sons.
"Alright, the child will live in the palace," he began, eliciting a sigh of relief from his wife. "However," he added, "you will be executed."
The advisor and Queen Eirwen shared a horrified glance. She lowered her gaze gently. "Yes, Your Highness," she said, bowing.
The King of Ice ordered the royal advisor to take the child to one of the vacant apartments in Eirwen's palace. Once this was done, he commanded the guards to lead Eirwen to the execution site, where all the villagers could witness the spectacle.
As the guards escorted her to the site, the villagers cried out in indignation at seeing their only queen, the kindest, about to be killed. Some people wept, others screamed and tried to attack the guards, while still others wondered what was happening, but all were outraged.
"Release her!"
"Why are they doing this to her?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden gallows, the most feared person in the kingdom made his entrance. The user of fire. Ex-Queen Eirwen was to be burned alive. No one deserved such a death, not even criminals. It was the cruelest punishment in Frostfell.
Eirwen was tied to the gallows, and the king began to explain how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of Frostfell refused to believe him and never accepted his words. Then, the user of fire set the gallows ablaze, and a single tear rolled down the cheek of the ex-queen.
"Survive, Kari." That was the end of Queen Eirwen's reign.
Silence in the corridors
Tap, tap, tap. These were the only sounds emanating from the farthest room to the left in the south wing of the still frozen palace. Servants passing by still wondered what was in that room, terrified of what might be inside. Whispers among the maids danced down the halls. It was believed that the late wife of the King of Ice, Eirwen, was in that room, waiting to be released.
"They could not possibly be more wrong," Ivory thought as she walked towards the south wing, while the servants went about murmuring to each other. They have no idea at all what is in that room.
Of course, these rumors applied to iel as well, since iel was the only person authorized to enter the room.
Knock Knock. "Miss Kari, are you there?" Ivory murmured at the finely decorated door, covered in snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Iel wondered if she would invite him in, unlike the other times when iel had asked. I still have bruises from the last time. Ivory giggled at the memory. Kari had thrown a book at iel's shoulder, but when she realized who it was, she immediately apologized.
A single knock came from inside, which seemed to mean she was there, but then again, where else could she be?
"May I enter?" asked Ivory, remembering the time iel did so without asking for permission.
A knock echoed from inside. It seemed to want to say yes. Ivory shivered, from the cold but also because of the sound. It was strange for Ivory to hear any noise coming from what was supposed to be an empty room, even though iel had entered this room for years.
"I am here," said Ivory, opening the door gently. The scene inside the room was unusual by normal standards, but not unexpected. Papers were scattered everywhere. Books were scattered about, the desk was broken, and numerous ice statues were scattered around. The room had no windows and almost no light. It was also much colder than the rest of the palace (and that was saying something). A snowstorm seemed to have fallen inside.
The girl was curled up on her bed, wrapped in her quilt, reading one of her notebooks. A small lantern illuminated the space.
"What notebook is it from?" asked Ivory, sitting next to Kari on her bed.
